-- ── Formsort ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Formsort is a low-code platform for building multi-step web forms and funnels with conditional logic, real-time calculations, and full design control, widely used for healthcare intake, eligibility screening, and clinical trial qualification flows.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (up to 100 flow starts/month); Pro from $279/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Formsort Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Formsort review: a low-code platform for multi-step forms and funnels used in healthcare intake and eligibility screening. See 2026 pricing and features.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Formsort is a low-code platform purpose-built for creating complex, multi-step web forms and conversion funnels, with a particular strength in conditional branching logic, real-time calculations, and complete design control over the resulting form experience. Unlike general-purpose form builders that optimize for simple, single-page lead-capture forms, Formsort is engineered for long, multi-step flows where the questions a user sees next depend on how they answered previous questions, a pattern that shows up constantly in healthcare intake, insurance eligibility screening, financial qualification, and, notably, patient screening and eligibility flows for clinical trials and telehealth services. In these use cases, a form functions less like a static contact form and more like a decision tree: advanced branching logic lets teams tailor which questions a respondent sees based on their prior answers, ensuring that a patient or applicant is only asked the specific criteria-relevant questions needed to determine eligibility for a given treatment, care pathway, or study, rather than a long, undifferentiated questionnaire that asks everyone every possible question. Formsort was founded in 2019 and is headquartered in New York City, with reported co-founders including Benjamin Fine and Fil Zembowicz, the latter of whom previously worked as an early employee and Head of Product at Better, a digital mortgage company, experience that plausibly informed Formsort's focus on long-form, multi-step, conditionally branching web flows in regulated or high-stakes domains like healthcare and financial services. Formsort has raised approximately $4 million in disclosed funding, a comparatively modest amount versus many venture-backed SaaS companies, from investors including Notation Capital, Cursor Capital, BoxGroup, Not Boring, and Quint Capital, suggesting the company has grown in a capital-efficient manner rather than pursuing an aggressive, heavily-funded growth strategy. Public revenue estimates place Formsort at roughly $990,000 in annual revenue with a reported team of around nine people, positioning it as a lean, focused team serving a relatively narrow but high-value niche rather than pursuing broad horizontal form-builder market share. Technically, Formsort is a low-code rather than no-code platform, meaning the visual flow-building interface is designed for product, growth, and clinical operations teams to configure without writing code for most use cases, while still exposing custom CSS, custom domains, and deeper technical configuration for teams that need to precisely match a form's design to their existing brand and product experience. Beyond conditional branching, Formsort supports real-time calculations within a flow, letting a form compute values, such as an eligibility score, an estimated cost, or a risk indicator, based on responses as the user progresses, and display or act on that calculated value before the flow is complete. The platform also supports split testing of different flow variants, native Stripe payment collection within a flow, Salesforce integration for pushing qualified leads or completed applications directly into a CRM, and detailed form analytics for understanding where users drop off within a multi-step flow, a capability that is particularly valuable given how much conversion rate can hinge on exactly where friction occurs in a long qualification process. On pricing, Formsort follows a three-tier freemium model measured in flow starts, meaning the number of times a user begins a given form flow, rather than raw form views or completed submissions. The Free plan allows up to 100 flow starts per month and includes unlimited users and forms, custom logo and color branding, though Formsort's own branding remains visible on forms built on this tier. The Pro plan costs approximately $279 per month billed monthly, or roughly $233 per month with annual billing (two months free), and increases the flow-start allowance to 1,000 per month while unlocking complete design control, custom data submission frequency settings, support for returning respondents who resume a flow, custom CSS, a custom domain, split testing, Stripe payment collection, Salesforce integration, and form analytics. Additional flow starts beyond the Pro plan's included allowance are billed at approximately $239 per additional 1,000 flow starts. The Enterprise plan is priced on a custom, contact-sales basis for organizations exceeding 1,000 monthly flow starts, and adds HIPAA compliance, support for multiple environments (such as separate staging and production instances), advanced roles and permissions, an option to store submission data entirely outside Formsort's own systems for organizations with strict data residency requirements, and a dedicated implementation manager to support onboarding and configuration. The explicit availability of HIPAA compliance at the Enterprise tier underscores how central healthcare and other regulated use cases are to Formsort's business, distinguishing it from most general-purpose form and funnel builders that do not offer, or do not prominently market, HIPAA-compliant configurations. Formsort's target customer is typically a healthcare, insurtech, fintech, or telehealth company's product, growth, or clinical operations team that needs to build and iterate quickly on a complex, branching qualification or intake flow, often one directly tied to revenue or regulatory compliance, such as determining insurance eligibility, screening patients for a specific treatment or clinical trial, or qualifying leads for a regulated financial product. Within the broader form and funnel-building category, Formsort competes against general-purpose multi-step form and quiz builders like Typeform and Outgrow on one side, and against fully custom, hand-coded internal engineering solutions on the other, positioning itself as a middle path that gives non-engineering teams the ability to build and iterate on sophisticated branching logic and calculations without requiring a full custom engineering build for every new flow or variant, while still offering the HIPAA compliance and design control that regulated industries require.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '2118c9da-01b6-493f-b26d-224cc4de5ba8';

